<br>
I'm going to try to summarize it very simply so we can throw it out and talk about it.<br>
<br>
The mob is beating on you, does this mean you are at the top of the aggro list?<br>
<br>
No<br>
<br>
It means you're on the top of the aggro list of the people close enough for the mob to beat on without moving his lazy butt.  But people further away could and likely DO have more generated aggro than you, there seems to be a point where the mob sees it as so severe that he needs to do something about it, like move or summon.   Summonning is a good thing in this case because it rids the world of another wizard and you can get on with your merry lives, but moving is incredibly bad.  Ping pong is a bad thing because then YOU are the one high on the aggro list but too far away.<br>
<br>
There seems also to be a time period after summonning that the rules of proximity are overridden.   In other words, for some short amount of time after you're summonned, you have TOTAL control of the mob's position, and can move him at will, he'll follow you no matter what.<br>
<br>
Any other time, you can be tanking a mob, and it's position needs adjustment, and you walk away only for him to turn and beat on someone else, because you seem to have crossed that &quot;hate/proximity&quot; barrier.<br>
<br>
OK, in this type of situation (where a lot of people are doing lots of damage from a long way away), it would seem that mashing is probably most appropriate because on a successful taunt it ensures that you are not only highest on the hate list of those close enough for the mob to care about, but actually places you above EVERYONE else.   In other words, adding numerical hate to you that you wouldn't have otherwise had EVEN IF you have the mob's attention.   <br>
<br>
In a situation where there isn't as much proximity (in tight quarters fighting, or standard experience grouping), it would seem that taunting upon loss of aggro is the most efficient.<br>
<br>
Anyone care to correct me?<br>
