<br>
out of habit mostly <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.thirdage.com/Adventure/alisonpv/saraney.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Officer of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub58.ezboard.com/biris83174">Iris</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ragnok>Ragnok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/17/03 12:36:50 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: taunt</span><hr size=1> There are a few things in this game that give me great pleasure to see. One would be when a chanter dies and a bard immediately mezzes 3 mobs to save the party. The second is when a chanter keeps 8+ mobs mezzed to save the party. The third, and my favorite, are very well placed taunts (I'm bias). <br>
<br>
For Instance, I pull a mob. I run back to the party, and stand next to the shaman (prevents ping pong). The mob reaches me and the party. 90% of warriors at this point feel an unresistable urge to start mashing the taunt button. Lets call it the Turge. The turge is an evil thing, a bad thing. avoid the turge. The turge is your enemy. The turge is also your casters' enemy. The mob reaches me, and i resist the turge. I look at my text window and see that my shaman starts to cast a spell. I know what that spell is. I know that when the shaman lands that slow in the next 2 seconds, the mob will turn from me to the shaman. but im ready. i resisted the turge. the very instant that i see that slow hit the mob, i finally hit taunt. The mob turns to me without ever touching the shaman. The mob looks to have done what amounts to a double take. He looked at the shammy and then immediately back at me. This is what you should see in your window:<br>
<br>
Shammy begins to cast a spell<br>
A mob hits you for x damage<br>
A mob bashes you for x damage<br>
A mob hits you for x damage<br>
A mob Yawns.<br>
You taunt a mob to ignore everyone and attack you!<br>
<br>
    How could i do this?? How could I land that taunt exactly after the shammy landed the slow? My friends, I resisted the turge, and taunt was ready to use when it was needed. I didnt taunt as soon as the mob returned. Why would I? I already have agro. And because taunt wasnt already spent for a precious 5 seconds, I was ready to use it as skillfully as a surgeon uses his knife.<br>
<br>
Half of this is about saving the shaman 2 bubbles of health because you didnt waste your taunt when the mob reached your party. The second half, my friends, is simple finesse. <br>
<br>
The moral of this story, is to resist the turge, and to anticipate the very second when that slow is gonna land, or any other large agro spell for that matter. With a group that knows what they are doing, I think the slow is the only time you can expect to so blatently lose agro. The turge is bad. its evil. Avoid turging at all cost. Your slowers will just love you for it.<br>
<br>
Ragnok Gemcrusher<br>
63 Warlord<br>
Divine Prophecy<br>
